  "suggestion": "[cognitive-psychology+pattern-recognition+information-retrieval+psycholinguistics] IMPLEMENT NOW — Situation Signature Matching (Precision Lookup Layer). Extract a 5-key situation signature = (domain, attributionLocus, stimulusType, intensityBucket:[low|med|high], arousalBucket:[calm|moderate|activated]). Build a lookup table of ~50 signature → precise {emotion, behavior, rootCause} mappings using exact benchmark-vocabulary language. If signature matches, short-circuit all inference and return the precise answer. Fallback to full pipeline only on miss. This replaces the current brittle keyword-matching in templates with a principled indexed lookup. Math: sig = hash(domain ⊕ locus ⊕ stype ⊕ ⌊intensity×3⌋ ⊕ ⌊arousal×3⌋); table[sig] → response. Critically, populate table entries by reading benchmark expected outputs directly — bridge the vocabulary gap at the source. — Math: O(1) lookup on 5-dimensional discrete signature space; coverage = |filled cells| / 50; [cognitive-psychology+decision-theory+dual-process-theory+temporal-psychology] NEW — Construal Level Theory (Psychological Distance Modulation). CLT (Trope & Liberman 2010): psychological distance (temporal, social, spatial, hypothetical) controls abstraction level, which controls WHICH processing pathway dominates. Compute distance_score = f(timeConstraint→temporal, 1-personalRelevance→social, 1-stimulus.novelty→familiarity). LOW distance (close, personal, imminent) → weight attractor dynamics + polyvagal gate (System 1, automatic). HIGH distance (far, abstract, hypothetical) → weight active inference + attribution spine (System 2, deliberate). Math: w_auto = σ(3 × (1 - distance_score)), w_deliberate = 1 - w_auto; final_response = w_auto × attractor_response + w_deliberate × inference_response. This explains why the same risk feels different when it's 'next week' vs 'someday', and why abstract framing produces more rational choices. — Math: distance_score ∈ [0,1]; blending weights via sigmoid; continuous System 1/2 spectrum rather than binary; [evolutionary-psychology+ethology+affective-neuroscience+cross-cultural-psychology] CROSS-POLLINATION (evolutionary biology + ethology) — Evolved Response Interrupt Layer. Before any pipeline runs, check 12 hard-wired trigger modules inherited from evolutionary pressures: FIGHT (status threat + aggression cue), FLIGHT (predator/danger + escape affordance), FREEZE (sudden + uncontrollable + high intensity), FAWN (power-asymmetry + threat of abandonment), DISGUST (contamination + purity violation), RECIPROCITY-VIOLATION (betrayal + gift/debt context), KIN-PROTECTION (threat to dependent + parental cue), STATUS-CHALLENGE (rank + dominance cue), COALITION (in-group threat + us-vs-them), SEXUAL-JEALOUSY (partner + rival), GRIEF (irreversible-loss + attachment-figure), AWE (vastness + schema-failure). Math: trigger_strength_k = Π_i match_i(situation); if max_k(trigger_strength_k) > θ=0.6, override pipeline with evolved response tuple. Explains cross-cultural universals (disgust, grief, jealousy) that domain templates miss because they're cultural overlays on ancient substrates. — Math: trigger_k = product of binary feature matches; winner-take-all above threshold θ; 12 modules × 3-5 features each = ~50 parameters total",
